quran[26]{c,v,t,f}:
53,1,"By the star when it sets: {1}",footnotes:1:In the original the word an-najm has been used. Ibn Abbas
53,2,"your companion {1} has neither strayed nor is he deluded; {2}",footnotes:1:Your companion: implies the Messenger of Allah (peace be upon him) and the addressees are the Quraish. The word Sahib as used in the original means a friend
53,3,"nor does he speak out of his desire."
53,4,"This is nothing but a revelation that is conveyed to him, {1}",footnotes:1:It means this: The things for which you accuse him of having gone astray or been misled and deceived
53,5,"something that a very powerful one has imparted to him, {1}",footnotes:1:That is
53,6,"one endowed with immense wisdom. {1} He came forth and stood poised,",footnotes:1:Ibn Abbas and Qatadah take dhu mirra-tin of the text in the meaning of beautiful and grand. Mujahid
53,7,"being on the higher horizon. {1}",footnotes:1:The horizon means the eastern edge of the sky where the sun rises and the day dawns. The same has been referred to as ufuq-mubin (bright horizon) in( Surah Takweer
53,8,"Then he drew near and hung above suspended,"
53,9,"until he was two bows' length away, or nearer. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
53,10,"Then he revealed to Allah's servant whatever he had to reveal. {1}",footnotes:1:The sentence faauha ila abdihi ma auha of the text can have two translations:
53,11,"His heart added no untruth to what he saw. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
53,12,"Are you, then, going to contend with him regarding what he sees with his eyes?"
53,13,"Indeed he saw him a second time,"
53,14,"by the lote-tree at the farthest boundary,"
53,15,"near which is the Garden of Abode. {1}",footnotes:1:This is about the Holy Prophet’s second meeting with Gabriel in which he appeared before him in his real shape and nature. The place where this meeting took place has been described as Sidrat-al-muntaha
53,16,"(This was) when the lote-tree was covered with that which covered it. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
53,17,"His eye did not waver, nor did it stray, {1}",footnotes:1:That is
53,18,"and he certainly saw some of the greatest Signs of His Lord. {1}",footnotes:1:This verse clearly states that the Prophet (peace be upon him) had not seen Allah but His wonderful sings. Even according to the context
53,19,"Have you ever thought about al-Lat and al-Uzza, {1}",footnotes:1:That is
53,20,"and about the third deity, al-Manat?"
53,21,"Shall you have the male issues, and He the female issues? {1}",footnotes:1:That is
53,22,"That is indeed an unfair division!"
53,23,"These are nothing but names that you and your forefathers have invented, for which Allah has sent down no authority. {1} They are merely following their conjectures and their carnal desires {2} although guidance has come to them from their Lord. {3}",footnotes:1:That is
53,24,"Does man imagine that whatever he wishes for is right for him? {1}",footnotes:1:Another meaning of this verse can be: Is man entitled to take anyone he pleases as his god? Still another meaning can be: Can the desire of man to have his prayers answered by these gods ever be fulfilled?
53,25,"To Allah belong both the Next World and the present."
53,26,"Numerous are the angels in the heavens; yet their intercession shall be of no avail, except in regard to those whom He grants the leave of intercession and whose plea He is pleased to accept. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
